<fit4bit-main-content-container [title]="'Hier kannst du einloggen'">
  <fit4bit-base-item-card [large]="true">
    <form
      fxLayout="column"
      fxLayoutAlign="center center"
      [formGroup]="profileForm"
      (ngSubmit)="login()"
    >
      <mat-form-field>
        <mat-label for="username">Email</mat-label>
        <input id="username" matInput type="text" formControlName="username" />
      </mat-form-field>

      <mat-form-field>
        <mat-label for="password">Passwort</mat-label>
        <input id="password" matInput type="text" formControlName="password" />
      </mat-form-field>

      <button
        mat-raised-button
        color="primary"
        type="submit"
        [disabled]="!profileForm.valid"
      >
        Speichern
      </button>
    </form>
  </fit4bit-base-item-card>
</fit4bit-main-content-container>

components.template:
Pages in Storybook

We recommend building UIs with a component-driven process starting with atomic components and ending with pages.

Render pages with mock data. This makes it easy to build and review page states without needing to navigate to them in your app. Here are some handy patterns for managing page data in Storybook:

  • Use a higher-level connected component. Storybook helps you compose such data from the "args" of child component stories
  • Assemble data in the page component from your services. You can mock these services out using Storybook.

Get a guided tutorial on component-driven development at Storybook tutorials . Read more in the docs .

Tip Adjust the width of the canvas with the Viewports addon in the toolbar

We recommend building UIs with a component-driven process starting with atomic components and ending with pages.

  • Use a higher-level connected component. Storybook helps you compose such data from the "args" of child component stories
  • Assemble data in the page component from your services. You can mock these services out using Storybook.

Get a guided tutorial on component-driven development at Storybook tutorials . Read more in the docs .

Tip Adjust the width of the canvas with the Viewports addon in the toolbar

components.name: TrainingComponent
components.templateData:
<fit4bit-main-content-container [title]="'Neues Training erfassen'">
  <form
    fxLayout="column"
    fxLayoutAlign="center center"
    [formGroup]="formGroup"
    (ngSubmit)="create()"
    fxLayoutAlign="center center"
  >
    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Raum</mat-label>
      <mat-select formControlName="roomId">
        <mat-option *ngFor="let room of roomsDtoList" [value]="room.id">
          {{ room.name }}
        </mat-option>
      </mat-select>
    </mat-form-field>

    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Typ</mat-label>
      <mat-select formControlName="trainingTypId">
        <mat-option
          *ngFor="let trainingTyp of trainingTypList"
          [value]="trainingTyp.id"
        >
          {{ trainingTyp.name }}
        </mat-option>
      </mat-select>
    </mat-form-field>

    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Trainer</mat-label>
      <mat-select formControlName="userId">
        <mat-option *ngFor="let user of userList" [value]="user.id">
          {{ user.firstName }} {{ user.email }}
        </mat-option>
      </mat-select>
    </mat-form-field>

    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Dauer [min]</mat-label>
      <input
        matInput
        placeholder="Minuten"
        type="number"
        formControlName="duration"
      />
    </mat-form-field>

    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Datum</mat-label>
      <input matInput [matDatepicker]="picker" formControlName="startDate" />
      <mat-datepicker-toggle matSuffix [for]="picker"></mat-datepicker-toggle>
      <mat-datepicker #picker></mat-datepicker>
    </mat-form-field>

    <mat-form-field appearance="fill">
      <mat-label>Startzeit</mat-label>
      <input
        matInput
        placeholder="Start Zeit"
        type="string"
        formControlName="startTime"
      />
    </mat-form-field>

    <button
      mat-raised-button
      color="primary"
      type="submit"
      [disabled]="!formGroup.valid"
    >
      Speichern
    </button>
  </form>
</fit4bit-main-content-container>
